On Yom HaShoah, Holocaust Remembrance Day, President Joe Biden issued a proclamation calling for a week of observance of the Days of Remembrance of Victims of the Holocaust. The proclamation reflects on the horrors of the Holocaust when millions of innocent people, including 6 million Jews, were systematically murdered by the Nazi regime. The president emphasizes the importance of remembering the truth of what happened during the Holocaust, as well as honoring the memories of the victims and embracing the survivors. He highlights the shared responsibility of ensuring that the Holocaust is never erased from collective memory, especially as fewer survivors remain. The president also emphasizes the need for action against antisemitism and other forms of hatred, as well as the importance of educating future generations about the Holocaust. He condemns Holocaust denial and distortion, recognizing them as forms of antisemitism. The administration has taken steps to combat antisemitism, including partnering with the German government to improve Holocaust education and appointing a special envoy to monitor and combat antisemitism. The president also signed legislation and implemented measures to combat crimes based on various forms of discrimination. He met with Auschwitz survivors to bear witness to their stories and combat Holocaust denial and distortion. The president calls on the people of the United States to observe the week of remembrance and remember the victims and survivors of the Holocaust, standing against antisemitism and all forms of hate.